        description: "Saint-Cirq-Lapopie, a village perched above the Lot river and voted 'Most Beautiful Village of France', is 1h30 from Toulouse.",
        routeDescription: "The route takes the A62 then the A20 towards Cahors, exit to the D662 along the Lot.",
        introduction: "Saint-Cirq-Lapopie is arguably France's most photogenic village: a medieval eagle's nest perched 100 metres above a meander of the Lot, in a landscape of limestone cliffs, oak forests and emerald water. This village of 200 inhabitants, listed among the 'Most Beautiful Villages of France' and voted the nation's favourite village in 2012, has bewitched artists for centuries. Andre Breton, the father of surrealism, bought a house here in 1950 and declared: 'Saint-Cirq-Lapopie: I have stopped wishing to be elsewhere.' Art and literature permeate every stone. Houses from the 13th to 16th centuries, with brown-tiled roofs cascading down the cliff, house artisan workshops (wood turners, coppersmiths — the village's traditional trades). The 15th-century fortified church offers a vertiginous panorama over the Lot valley from its terrace. Below, the towpath follows the Lot to restored 19th-century locks. The Pech-Merle decorated cave (25 km), with its 25,000-year-old prehistoric paintings (spotted horses, negative hands), completes this exceptional cultural excursion. A taxi from Toulouse is the most practical way to reach this isolated site with no direct public transport.",
        itineraire: "From Toulouse, your driver takes the A62 then the A20 towards Cahors. After Montauban, the motorway crosses the Quercy limestone plateaux, cut by the Lot and Cele valleys. You leave the A20 at Cahors-Nord exit (exit 57) for the D653 then the D662, which follows the Lot eastward. This final section is the most beautiful: the road follows the Lot's meanders, hemmed between limestone cliffs colonised by holm oaks. You pass through several stone villages before spotting Saint-Cirq-Lapopie, appearing atop its cliff like an apparition. Arrival is at the viewpoint car park (at the top) or the Tour-de-Faure car park (below, by the Lot). A62 + A20 tolls total approximately €9. The journey takes 1h30 normally and can reach 1h50 in summer, as the D662 is busy with canoeists and campers.",
        conseils: "The upper car park gives direct access to the village through the main gate — the most practical option by taxi. The village takes 1h30 to explore on foot (lanes, church, panoramas), plus 30 min for the towpath below. The Maison Andre Breton, now an artists' residence, is open in summer. The Rignault Museum (contemporary art, lovely Lot-view terrace) is worth a detour. For a complete experience, combine Saint-Cirq with the Pech-Merle cave (25 km, booking essential in summer, limited to 700 visitors/day): the 25,000-year-old spotted horses are among Europe's finest cave paintings. Le Gourmet Quercynois restaurant serves duck confit and cabecou with a valley view. In summer, canoeing on the Lot between Saint-Cirq and Bouzies (1h30, easy) is a magical activity — the driver can collect you downstream.",
        comparaisonTransport: "No direct public transport from Toulouse. The nearest TER serves Cahors (1h15, €18), from where you need a Lio bus (€2, 40 min, only 2 departures/day) or a local taxi (€30). The total journey takes at least 2h30 with uncertain connections. By car, expect €14 in fuel and €9 in tolls. The TaxiNeo taxi at €140 — €180 is the only realistic solution for a day trip: direct journey in 1h30, the driver waits during your visit. For 4 passengers, the cost (€35-45 per person) is comparable to train + bus + local taxi, for incomparably greater comfort.",
